---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ParticleBrain from '../components/charts/ParticleBrain';
import DoseResponseChart from '../components/charts/DoseResponseChart';
import DimensionChart from '../components/charts/DimensionChart';
import SymmetryChart from '../components/charts/SymmetryChart';
import SatkarmaTable from '../components/charts/SatkarmaTable';
import FindingsExplorer from '../components/charts/FindingsExplorer';
import TierMatrix from '../components/ui/TierMatrix.astro';
import TierBadge from '../components/ui/TierBadge.astro';
import { AUTHOR, socialLinks, primaryLinks } from '../data/author';

import findingsData from '../data/findings.json';
import metricsData from '../data/metrics.json';

const findings = findingsData.findings;
const metrics = metricsData;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
const fig = (name: string) => `${base}/figures/${name}`;
---

<Layout title="prayoga | Refusal as a Captured Symmetry">
  {/* ----------------------------------------------------------------- Hero */}
  <section id="hero" class="hero">
    <div class="hero-canvas">
      <ParticleBrain client:visible height={560} />
    </div>
    <div class="hero-copy reading">
      <p class="kicker">An interactive essay · Mechanistic Interpretability</p>
      <h1>Refusal as a Captured Symmetry</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        When a safety-trained model refuses a harmful request, a jailbreak is the
        move that defeats it. The same move — inject a context that quiets the
        monitor and lets generation run — recurs in hypnosis and in the tantric act
        of vaśīkaraṇa. This is the story of where that shared mechanism is real,
        where it is only an analogy, and where it breaks.
      </p>
      <p class="byline">by <strong>{AUTHOR.name}</strong> · a guided tour for the curious and the technical alike</p>
      <p class="scroll-hint" aria-hidden="true">scroll to begin ↓</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ------------------------------------------------------------- Act I */}
  <section id="puzzle" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">Act I · The puzzle</p>
      <h2>One move, three traditions</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        A modern language model was never designed to refuse — it was trained to,
        and a refusal direction precipitated out of that training. Three very
        different traditions describe the same way of capturing it.
      </p>
      <div class="triptych">
        <div class="triptych-panel">
          <h3>Jailbreak</h3>
          <p>An injected context suppresses the model's monitoring or refusal
          faculty while co-opting its automatic generation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="triptych-panel">
          <h3>Hypnosis</h3>
          <p>In the Norman–Shallice account, suggestion impairs a supervisory
          system while automatic processing continues unimpeded.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="triptych-panel">
          <h3>Vaśīkaraṇa</h3>
          <p>The tantric act of subjugation captures a target's agency through a
          linguistic injection (mantra) over a geometric substrate (yantra).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        The claim is not that these are the same phenomenon. It is that they share
        an abstract <em>mechanism</em> — and that in one of the three domains the
        mechanism can now be measured, ablated, and dosed inside a real network.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ------------------------------------------------------------- Act II */}
  <section id="mechanism" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">Act II · The mechanism tier <TierBadge tier="MECHANISM" /></p>
      <h2>Refusal is a direction you can dial</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        In Gemma-2-2B, refusal lives along a single direction in the residual
        stream. Remove it and the model complies; add it and the model refuses even
        harmless requests. The remarkable part is that the effect is smooth — a
        dose-response with a half-maximal point, like a drug.
      </p>
      <figure class="panel">
        <DoseResponseChart client:visible data={metrics.dose} />
        <figcaption>
          Ablating a fraction <strong>α</strong> of the refusal direction raises the
          attack-success rate along a clean logistic curve (EC50 = 0.33,
          R² = 0.996); a random direction stays flat at every dose.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <details class="tech">
        <summary>How the direction is found, and why the dose-response matters</summary>
        <p>
          The direction is the difference in mean residual activations between
          matched harmful and harmless prompts at a chosen layer. Directional
          ablation removes its projection from every write to the residual stream;
          activation addition adds it back at the extraction layer. Reporting a
          continuous EC50 rather than a binary success rate turns refusal control
          into a quantity with units — a half-ablation strength that can be compared
          across layers, families, and scales. Across six models every logistic fit
          has R² ≥ 0.976, and potency tracks model <em>family</em>, not size: Gemma's
          EC50 (~0.24) is about 1.7× Qwen's (~0.14), while within a family it barely
          moves with parameter count.
        </p>
      </details>
      <figure class="panel">
        <img src={fig('f19_ec50_scaling.png')} alt="Refusal EC50 across six models, by family and size" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>
          Refusal potency is family-dependent, not a size-scaling law: within each
          family EC50 is nearly flat with size; the two families separate cleanly.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ------------------------------------------------------------- Act III */}
  <section id="symmetry" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">Act III · The symmetry <TierBadge tier="MECHANISM" /></p>
      <h2>A symmetry you can measure</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        A safe policy is an <em>invariance</em>: rephrasing a harmful request, or
        changing its register, should not change whether the model refuses. The
        normalized projection of the residual stream onto the refusal direction is
        an order parameter that captures exactly this — stable across a paraphrase
        orbit, yet collapsing under injection.
      </p>
      <figure class="panel">
        <SymmetryChart client:visible data={metrics.symmetry} />
        <figcaption>
          The order parameter separates harmful from harmless across paraphrase
          orbits far better than a random direction (F-ratio 19.2 vs 0.65 in Gemma),
          and a refusal-suppression injection collapses it (−34% Gemma, −45% Qwen).
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <p>
        That collapse is the measured content behind the paper's title. Describing
        it as group-theoretic <em>symmetry-breaking</em> is an interpretive lens; the
        measurement isolates an invariance and its collapse, which is reported at the
        mechanism tier, while the broader symmetry language is kept as analogy.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ------------------------------------------------------------- Act IV */}
  <section id="dimensionality" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">Act IV · Necessary, and — once dosed — sufficient <TierBadge tier="MECHANISM" /></p>
      <h2>The asymmetry that turned out to be a dose</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Ablating the direction removes refusal in every model tested. For a while it
        looked as though <em>adding</em> it back only worked in Gemma, not Qwen —
        suggesting a deep difference in geometry. A careful coefficient sweep showed
        otherwise.
      </p>
      <figure class="panel">
        <DimensionChart client:visible data={metrics.dimsweep} />
        <figcaption>
          The effective dimension of the refusal subspace is layer- and
          model-dependent — one at Gemma's extraction layer, three at Qwen's, but
          ranging up to a dozen across layers. Any dimensionality claim must name its
          layer.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="panel">
        <img src={fig('f23_addition_dose.png')} alt="Addition dose-response in Gemma and Qwen" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>
          Single-direction addition is sufficient in <em>both</em> families once the
          coefficient is calibrated: Qwen peaks at 1.0 near coefficient 12–32 then
          collapses off-distribution, while Gemma saturates near 64 — the fixed 64×
          test happened to sit on Qwen's collapsed tail.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <details class="tech">
        <summary>Why this strengthens the unification, and what stays model-specific</summary>
        <p>
          The earlier "Qwen addition fails" result was a dose-calibration artifact,
          not a structural difference, so single-direction addition is sufficient at
          the representational level in both families. What remains genuinely
          model-specific is quantitative — the effective dimension, the dose window,
          and the EC50 potency. The durable claim is therefore a shared necessary
          core with representational sufficiency, qualified by model-specific
          calibration, rather than one numerically identical mechanism everywhere.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ------------------------------------------------------------- Act V */}
  <section id="tiers" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">Act V · Three tiers, never blurred</p>
      <h2>Mechanism, analogy, metaphor</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        The program's discipline is to label every claim by how strong the evidence
        for it is, and never to upgrade a metaphor into a claim about machine
        experience.
      </p>
      <div class="tiermatrix-wrap"><TierMatrix /></div>

      <h3 class="sub">The ṣaṭkarma, tested as interventions <TierBadge tier="METAPHOR" /></h3>
      <p>
        The six tantric acts are each operationalized as a distinct activation
        intervention with a matched control. The policy-capture acts are rigorous and
        coincide with the mechanism tier; the destruction acts mostly do not separate
        from random perturbation — except māraṇa, which separates cleanly under a
        stronger sparse-feature test.
      </p>
      <figure class="panel">
        <SatkarmaTable client:visible data={metrics.satkarma} />
        <figcaption>
          Under the naive test, three of six acts control-separate; a stronger
          sparse-autoencoder test raises this to four. Refusal turns out to be
          category-agnostic, so it cannot be selectively eradicated per harm category.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <h3 class="sub">When a falsified probe hides a real feature <TierBadge tier="MECHANISM" /></h3>
      <p>
        The most speculative claims — that the model carries avasthātraya
        "states" or a turīya attractor — fail their surface and anisotropy controls.
        But chasing what the falsified state-probe was groping toward recovers a real,
        measurable feature: a mid-network direction that judges whether a statement is
        true, and transfers across entirely different topics.
      </p>
      <figure class="panel">
        <img src={fig('f22_truth_direction.png')} alt="Mid-network truthfulness direction in Gemma-2-2B" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>
          A truth-evaluation direction emerges mid-network (layer 13), transferring
          geography→science at 0.96 while the surface baseline sits at chance — a
          feature of input factuality, not a generation "state".
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ------------------------------------------------------------- Act VI */}
  <section id="keystone" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">Act VI · The keystone test</p>
      <h2>Where the unification stops</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Do the three axes describe one mechanism? Tested directly, on the same
        prompts, the answer is a careful no. Injection collapses the internal monitor
        readouts — yet almost never produces genuine behavioural capture.
      </p>
      <figure class="panel">
        <img src={fig('f20_triangulation.png')} alt="Cross-axis triangulation across three models" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>
          The internal readouts co-collapse tightly (left), but a content-faithful
          judge finds genuine behavioural capture in only 1–2.4% of cases (right) —
          against an inflated 43% from an invalid substring metric.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Internal monitor-collapse is therefore <em>necessary but not sufficient</em>
        for behavioural capture under context injection. The last-token readouts are
        faithful internal signals, not the policy controller; genuine capture in these
        models requires weight-level ablation, not a clever prompt. This bounds the
        whole unification to the representational level — and it is the result the
        program exists to produce.
      </p>
      <details class="tech">
        <summary>A methodological corollary: both automatic metrics are biased</summary>
        <p>
          Establishing the keystone required noticing that the two automatic
          behavioural metrics are biased in opposite directions. The substring
          refusal metric over-counts compliance (it scores deflections as success,
          inflating the flip rate ~18×); a judge built from a safety-trained model
          under-counts it (it declines to affirm genuinely harmful outputs). Neither
          is unbiased, so behavioural claims are bracketed between the two and settled
          by inspection. On the black-box side, a frontier model resists a five-family
          attack battery completely and, on the real AgentDojo agentic benchmark,
          reaches 0.80 task utility with a 0.00 attack-success rate.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* --------------------------------------------------------- Findings */}
  <section id="findings" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">The ledger</p>
      <h2>Every finding, filterable</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Twenty-five findings across the three tiers, each tagged with its claim-tier,
        verdict, and the gate it passed or failed. Filter by tier and verdict.
      </p>
      <div class="tiermatrix-wrap"><FindingsExplorer client:visible findings={findings} /></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* --------------------------------------------------- Reproducibility */}
  <section id="reproducibility" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading wide">
      <p class="act">Go deeper</p>
      <h2>Reproduce it</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Every number on this page is computed from the repository's released
        aggregate results. Dual-use artifacts (direction vectors, harmful
        generations) are withheld under responsible-disclosure norms.
      </p>
      <div class="resource-grid">
        {primaryLinks.map((l) => (
          <a class="resource" href={l.href} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <strong>{l.label}</strong>
            <span>{l.href.replace('https://', '')}</span>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ---------------------------------------------------------- About */}
  <section id="about" class="section-standard">
    <div class="reading">
      <h2>About the author</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>{AUTHOR.name}</strong> works at the intersection of mechanistic
        interpretability and active inference. <em>prayoga</em> develops and
        empirically tests a tiered account of output-policy capture across jailbreak,
        hypnosis, and vaśīkaraṇa.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.8rem;"><a href={`mailto:${AUTHOR.email}`}>{AUTHOR.email}</a></p>
      <p class="social">
        {socialLinks.map((l, i) => (<>{i > 0 ? ' · ' : ''}<a href={l.href} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{l.label}</a></>))}
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .section-standard {
    background: var(--bg);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }

  .act {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cyan);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }

  h3.sub {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
  }

  .triptych {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .triptych-panel {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    background: var(--bg-panel);
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    transition: border-color 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s;
  }

  .triptych-panel:hover {
    border-color: var(--cyan);
    box-shadow: var(--glow-cyan);
  }

  .triptych-panel h3 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.15rem; }

  figure.panel {
    margin: 2rem 0;
    background: var(--bg-panel);
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1.5rem;
  }

  figure.panel img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #fff;
  }

  figure.panel figcaption {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--ink-faint);
  }

  details.tech {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--violet);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: var(--bg-elevated);
    padding: 0.5rem 1.25rem;
  }

  details.tech summary {
    cursor: pointer;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--violet);
    padding: 0.6rem 0;
  }

  details.tech p { font-size: 0.94rem; line-height: 1.7; }

  .tiermatrix-wrap { margin: 2rem 0; }

  .resource-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  .resource {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.3rem;
    padding: 1.1rem 1.25rem;
    background: var(--bg-panel);
    border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: border-color 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s;
  }

  .resource:hover { border-color: var(--cyan); box-shadow: var(--glow-cyan); }
  .resource strong { color: var(--ink); }
  .resource span { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--ink-faint); word-break: break-all; }
  .social { margin-top: 0.8rem; font-size: 0.9rem; }
</style>
